Mistral
-------

The Wall Street Journal ( https://www.wsj.com/tech/ai/the-9-month-old-ai-st=
artup-challenging-silicon-valleys-giants-ee2e4c48 ) had a profile of Mistra=
l, the French AI startup building foundation models:

This time last year, Arthur Mensch was 30, still employed at a Google unit =
here, and artificial intelligence had just started to take off in the publi=
c consciousness as something more than science fiction. Since then, so-call=
ed generative AI that can converse=E2=80=94and possibly reason=E2=80=94like=
 humans has become the most talked-about technology breakthrough in decades=
. And the startup Mensch left Google to launch, now all of nine months old,=
 is valued at slightly more than $2 billion=E2=80=A6Mensch=E2=80=99s startu=
p, called Mistral AI, is challenging the conventional wisdom that the winne=
rs of the AI race will emerge from among the tech industry=E2=80=99s U.S. g=
iants. Mensch, who founded the company with two engineering-school friends,=
 doesn=E2=80=99t think enormous scale is essential =E2=80=94 or that the U.=
S. will necessarily dominate.

Mensch=E2=80=99s company, which has raised just over $500 million from inve=
stors including Andreessen Horowitz, remains tiny compared with the Goliath=
s of the industry. Microsoft-backed OpenAI and Alphabet=E2=80=99s Google ar=
e pouring billions of dollars into training the latest AI systems, leveragi=
ng their access to the specialized computer chips needed to build such syst=
ems and the fat balance sheets needed to pay for the electricity those chip=
s consume. Mistral, named for a strong wind that blows from France, is foun=
ded in part on the idea that a lot of that money is being wasted.

Mensch, who started in academia, has spent much of his life figuring out ho=
w to make AI and machine-learning systems more efficient. Early last year, =
he joined forces with co-founders Timoth=C3=A9e Lacroix, 32, and Guillaume =
Lample, 33, who were then at Meta Platforms=E2=80=99 artificial-intelligenc=
e lab in Paris. Together, they are betting that their small team can outman=
euver Silicon Valley titans by finding more efficient ways to build and dep=
loy AI systems. And they want to do it in part by giving away many of their=
 AI systems as open-source software. =E2=80=9CWe want to be the most capita=
l-efficient company in the world of AI,=E2=80=9D Mensch said. =E2=80=9CThat=
=E2=80=99s the reason we exist.=E2=80=9D

Mensch made his name at Google with the Chinchilla AI model, which demonstr=
ated that you could achieve superior results from a model with relatively f=
ewer parameters (i.e. smaller) that was trained on relatively more data. Mi=
stral also reportedly is extremely focused on the quality of data used to t=
rain its models; I=E2=80=99ve written in the past about the fact that trans=
formers can be trained on relatively poor data ( https://stratechery.com/20=
22/the-ai-unbundling/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZW=
NoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5w=
YXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJhenAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InV=
yaSI6WyJodHRwczovL3N0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LmNvbS8yMDIyL3RoZS1haS11bmJ1bmRsaW5nLyJdfS=
wiZXhwIjoxNzExNzE5MjU4LCJpYXQiOjE3MDkxMjcyNTgsImlzcyI6Imh0dHBzOi8vYXBpLnBhc=
