7o-wR9basgfA ) that generative AI use cases may not have materialized quite=
 to the extent that Nvidia=E2=80=99s earnings indicated; that said, there h=
ave two been two recent bits of news that speak to an area where generative=
 AI is both obviously useful and in fact already having an impact.

First is ServiceNow; ServiceNow is a cloud platform for managing IT service=
s, and has gradually expanded since its founding twenty years ago to be a c=
omprehensive enterprise platform for all sorts of backend functions; the co=
mpany moved quickly to incorporate generative AI into its products, and is =
already reaping the rewards. From SiliconAngle ( https://siliconangle.com/2=
024/01/24/servicenow-beats-guidance-metrics-generative-ai-powers-strong-gro=
wth/ ) :

Workflow software company ServiceNow Inc. posted stellar fourth-quarter res=
ults today, while its guidance for the first quarter and full year came in =
well ahead of estimates. Officials said the strong results were driven at l=
east partly by the company=E2=80=99s aggressive rollout of artificial intel=
ligence capabilities within its core software offerings=E2=80=A6The company=
 delivered results that came in ahead of Wall Street=E2=80=99s guidance on =
almost every metric, with subscription revenue coming to $2.365 billion, up=
 27% from a year earlier and ahead of the forecast of $2.32 billion. Total =
revenue came to $2.437 billion, beating the consensus estimate of $2.402 bi=
llion. Earnings before certain costs such as stock compensation came to $3.=
11 per share, beating the consensus of $2.78 by a comfortable margin. The c=
ompany=E2=80=99s adjusted operating margin was 29%, ahead of the Street=E2=
=80=99s forecast of 27.5%. Finally, current remaining performance obligatio=
ns came to $8.6 billion, up 24%, higher than the forecast of a 21% gain.

McDermott told Barron=E2=80=99s in an interview that the company is getting=
 close to hitting the $10 billion annual subscription revenue run-rate mile=
stone, thanks to the incorporation of so many AI features in its products. =
He added that many of the new features were rolled out in September, and ha=
ve already delivered a material impact on the company=E2=80=99s bottom line=
. =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99re seeing the largest net new contract contribution o=
f any product we have ever introduced,=E2=80=9D he said.

Second is Klarna, the buy-now-pay-later company; from Fast Company ( https:=
//www.fastcompany.com/91039401/klarna-ai-virtual-assistant-does-the-work-of=
-700-humans-after-layoffs ) :

One month after taking its OpenAI-powered virtual assistant global, the Swe=
dish buy-now, pay-later company has released new data touting its ability t=
o handle customer communications, make shoppers happier, and even drive bet=
ter financial results.

The app-based AI chatbot already handles two-thirds of all customer service=
 chats, the company said Tuesday =E2=80=94 some 2.3 million conversations s=
o far =E2=80=94 with the virtual assistant earning customer satisfaction ra=
tings at the same level as human agents. Klarna, which is expected to go pu=
blic this year and will need all the hype it can get at a time when investo=
rs have been generally frosty toward IPOs, estimates that the chatbot could=
 help improve its profits by $40 million in 2024=E2=80=A6Klarna boasted in =
its announcement on Tuesday that the AI assistant =E2=80=9Cis doing the equ=
ivalent work of 700 full-time agents.=E2=80=9D

Klarna is still a private company, so all numbers should be taken with the =
appropriate grain of salt, but this story is certainly believable: customer=
 support is, for a human, a pretty low throughput job that is only viable i=
f it is fairly low paid. This means the barrier for generative AI to be bet=
ter is fairly low: the cost advantage is already massive, and the hurdle ra=
te in terms of mistakes-per-interaction is pretty low. I would expect these=
 particular use cases =E2=80=94 especially customer support, both internal =
and external =E2=80=94 to be quickly dominated by generative AI. The utilit=
y is just so obvious, along with the potential cost savings.

More broadly, I suspect that AI is already having more of an impact on busi=
ness than is being measured: what is happening currently is that some numbe=
r of employees are effectively arbitraging AI, in that they are using AI to=
 do their job far more quickly and efficiently without reporting as such; t=
he task for companies over the coming quarters will be to capture that effi=
ciency by making AI =E2=80=9Cofficial=E2=80=9D as it were. Or, to put it an=
other way, while recommender systems may have been the inference that matte=
red last year, generative AI will likely swamp that sooner rather than late=
r.

